obscure private device provenance

Allow users to choose whether or not to reveal the provenance of the data to
consumers.  This is intended to help protect data rights to portability and
access.  If consumers start abusing or discriminating against Nightscout users
due to the source of the data, this allows users to conceal this information.

de facto standard LOW and HIGH values

Disregard brand of device when considering glucose values.  By de facto usage,
the meaning of LOW and HIGH within Nightscout means that glucose is beyond limits.
LOW means 40 or lower.  HIGH means 400 or higher.  Both tend to invite
questioning therapy options, including inspecting if the device is working
correctly, as well as potential treatment options.

ensure obfuscation only affects rendered values

The results to render may come from an in-memory cache, or from the database.
If they came from the in-memory cache, it's possible that obscurring the device
field could actually change the values in memory.  When obscurring, the device
field, this patch copies all of the values in order to ensure that the
in-memory copies are unaffected.  With this patch, cached objects should not be
affected.

Turns out I don't like fish-like auto-completion

Just drives me crazy
Kitty tweaks

Clean up vimrc

Some plugins I'm not using and some config that was redundant

Get rid of submodule references

We don't use submodules here (any more)

Integrate with kitty, clean up aliases

Lots of default aliases in the stuff I lifted that I'll never use. Let's
just get rid of them now.

Also, deeper integration with the kitty terminal program I use and love.

I no longer need the old zsh configuration files

Got everything I need out of them. Can remove them from disk now.

Get the dq command working

Moves this from oh-my-zsh to pure zsh so it works in the new setup.

Minor tweaks

Making some things better where I can.

Beautiful autocompletion for zsh

Oh. I like this. It's even better than what I had in oh-my-zsh.
Aliases update

Fixes for my work environment

This repairs everything I could find that was broken when I tried the
antidope stuff on my work MBPro. I had to ditch using plugins in a few
cases to get things to work. But load times are still super faaasst.

Adjust kitty colour settings

Messing around with more tab bar settings so my tabs are better
distinguished from things like my tmux windows and my tabs in vim.

Working antidote zsh configuration

Bootstrapping off the zdotdir project I was able to get a pretty decent
rework of my zsh environment going using antidote as the plugin manager.
The whole approach has greatly simplified my reliance on plugins. I've
moved a lot of the stuff into zshrc.d/*.zsh files now and done away with
the over use of the _has function -- I just load everything now as much
as it makes sense to do so.

TBD if this works with my work laptop where I have a greater reliance on
oh-my-zsh plugins, but on my home iMac it's pretty fly.

Get rake update working

This repairs the broken update target for zsh and drops submodule
updating since I'm not really using submodules at all any more.

Fix broken python initialization

Double init'ed python stuff and some of it was broken. This smooths
things out so it works nicely.

obscure private device provenance

Allow users to choose whether or not to reveal the provenance of the data to
consumers.  This is intended to help protect data rights to portability and
access.  If consumers start abusing or discriminating against Nightscout users
due to the source of the data, this allows users to conceal this information.

de facto standard LOW and HIGH values

Disregard brand of device when considering glucose values.  By de facto usage,
the meaning of LOW and HIGH within Nightscout means that glucose is beyond limits.
LOW means 40 or lower.  HIGH means 400 or higher.  Both tend to invite
questioning therapy options, including inspecting if the device is working
correctly, as well as potential treatment options.

ensure obfuscation only affects rendered values

The results to render may come from an in-memory cache, or from the database.
If they came from the in-memory cache, it's possible that obscurring the device
field could actually change the values in memory.  When obscurring, the device
field, this patch copies all of the values in order to ensure that the
in-memory copies are unaffected.  With this patch, cached objects should not be
affected.

Just drives me crazy
Kitty tweaks

Clean up vimrc

Some plugins I'm not using and some config that was redundant

Get rid of submodule references

We don't use submodules here (any more)

Integrate with kitty, clean up aliases

Lots of default aliases in the stuff I lifted that I'll never use. Let's
just get rid of them now.

Also, deeper integration with the kitty terminal program I use and love.

I no longer need the old zsh configuration files

Got everything I need out of them. Can remove them from disk now.

Get the dq command working

Moves this from oh-my-zsh to pure zsh so it works in the new setup.

Minor tweaks

Making some things better where I can.

Beautiful autocompletion for zsh

Oh. I like this. It's even better than what I had in oh-my-zsh.
Aliases update

Fixes for my work environment

This repairs everything I could find that was broken when I tried the
antidope stuff on my work MBPro. I had to ditch using plugins in a few
cases to get things to work. But load times are still super faaasst.

Adjust kitty colour settings

Messing around with more tab bar settings so my tabs are better
distinguished from things like my tmux windows and my tabs in vim.

Bootstrapping off the zdotdir project I was able to get a pretty decent
rework of my zsh environment going using antidote as the plugin manager.
The whole approach has greatly simplified my reliance on plugins. I've
moved a lot of the stuff into zshrc.d/*.zsh files now and done away with
the over use of the _has function -- I just load everything now as much
as it makes sense to do so.

TBD if this works with my work laptop where I have a greater reliance on
oh-my-zsh plugins, but on my home iMac it's pretty fly.

Get rake update working

This repairs the broken update target for zsh and drops submodule
updating since I'm not really using submodules at all any more.

Double init'ed python stuff and some of it was broken. This smooths
things out so it works nicely.

obscure private device provenance

Allow users to choose whether or not to reveal the provenance of the data to
consumers.  This is intended to help protect data rights to portability and
access.  If consumers start abusing or discriminating against Nightscout users
due to the source of the data, this allows users to conceal this information.

de facto standard LOW and HIGH values

Disregard brand of device when considering glucose values.  By de facto usage,
the meaning of LOW and HIGH within Nightscout means that glucose is beyond limits.
LOW means 40 or lower.  HIGH means 400 or higher.  Both tend to invite
questioning therapy options, including inspecting if the device is working
correctly, as well as potential treatment options.

ensure obfuscation only affects rendered values

The results to render may come from an in-memory cache, or from the database.
If they came from the in-memory cache, it's possible that obscurring the device
field could actually change the values in memory.  When obscurring, the device
field, this patch copies all of the values in order to ensure that the
in-memory copies are unaffected.  With this patch, cached objects should not be
affected.

3.2.5 - 2021-04-05 {#version-3-2-5}

Improvements

  • Add more validations to XPath parser.

  • Don't add #dcloe method to core classes globally. [GitHub#37][Patch by Akira Matsuda]
